Nepal
- Sarlahi District. 2 Dec 2016. Approximately 2 dozen dengue patients are being treated at Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital (STIDH). The majority of these patients are from Sarlahi district (Hariyon-11). According to them, there is construction work (Hariyon-11) going on nearby its surrounding area, probably making a favorable environment for mosquito breeding. Dengue was 1st reported in Lalitpur district in early September (this year, 2016) in Nepal [ProMED-mail archive http:// www.promedmail .org/post/ 20160912.4481482]. Since then, dengue has been reported from other parts of the country [ProMED-mail archive http://www.promedmail.org/post/ 20161031.4595998]. Currently, dengue has been detected from Sarlahi district, showing rapid geographic and demographic shifts (shifting from hilly, north, to lowland areas, south) in Nepal.

Contributed by: Dr. Sher Bahadur Pun, MD, Clinical Research Unit, Sukraraj Tropical and Infectious Disease Hospital, Kathmandu, Nepal <drsherbdr@yahoo.com>.

- Sibu. 30 Nov 2016. An increasing number of dengue cases have been detected in areas under Sibu Rural District Council (SRDC). Deputy chairman Robert Lau told a full council meeting yesterday that the total number of cases from January till October 2016 stood at 109, compared to 72 cases in the same period last year.
http://www.theborneopost.com/2016/11/30/dengue-cases-on-the-rise-in-srdc-areas/

- Rupandehi District. 16 Nov 2016. A total of 36 people in Rupandehi have been infected with dengue virus as of Tuesday [15 Nov 2016], said the District Public Health Office. Butwal city has outnumbered other cities and villages in the district housing dengue patients with 20 infected with dengue virus.
http://www.myrepublica.com/news/9258

- Rupandehi District. 25 Nov 2016. 196 dengue cases in Rupandehi. The number of people with this infection has gone up in the last 2 months.
http://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/196-found-dengue-infected-rupandehi/
- Mid-Western Region. 17 Nov. 2016. At least 64 cases of dengue have been reported in various districts of the Mid-Western Region in the last one and half months, according to the data of the Mid-Western Regional Health Directorate. The dengue-affected patients have received treatment at Bheri Zonal Hospital and Nepalgunj Medical College in Banke. Prakashraj Sharma, a health education officer at the directorate, said people from Banke, Bardiya, Dang, Rukum, Kalikot and Surkhet districts have been diagnosed with the disease. Nepalgunj Medical College has also provided treatment to 5 dengue-affected patients of Kailali district. The directorate said the majority of the patients have already returned home after receiving treatment. At least 13 people have been found infected with dengue in Surkhet alone in the past one month. Health officials said the majority of the patients were from Birendranagar. The district-based hospitals had referred dengue-infected patients to Nepalgunj due to lack of testing kits in Surkhet.
http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-11-17/64-cases-reported-in-18-months-in-mid-western-region.html

- Surkhet. 12 Nov 2016. Dengue downed at least 13 people in Surkhet in the past one month, the District Public Health Office (DPHO) said. Health officials said the majority of the patients were from Birendranagar. Udaya BC, the vector control supervisor of the DPHO, said that the disease is still spreading. Meanwhile, the district is running out of dengue testing kits. The DPHO has requested the centre to provide 200 dengue testing kits. Dengue patients have also been found in Bardiya, with at least 3 dozen cases reported in the last 2 weeks.
http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-11-12/dengue-found-in-surkhet.html

Bangladesh

- National. 3 Dec 2016. The country has this year [2016] seen the highest number of patients afflicted with dengue fever in the past 10 years.
The number of dengue cases has doubled to almost to 6000 this year [2016] compared to the past year. According to the disease control cell of the health department, a total of 5823 people were diagnosed with dengue fever from 1 Jan to 30 Nov this year [2016]. 10 of the patients have died this year [2016], records show.
http://en.prothom-alo.com/bangladesh/news/131339/Dengue-fever-cases-highest-this-year

India

Madhya Pradesh. 9 Nov 2016. 30 dengue cases reported 8 Nov 2016 with 11 cases of chikungunya
http://thehitavada.com/Encyc/2016/11/9/11-chikungunya,30-dengue-positive-patients-detected.aspx

Madhya Pradesh (Indore). 15 Nov 2016. On an average at least 300 patients admitted into private hospitals every month are suspected to have dengue fever, but not all of them are confirmed cases. While more than 3000 suspected dengue fever cases have been reported by city hospitals, only 109 were found confirmed in the last 10 months, according to health department records. http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/indore/Suspected-dengue-cases-high-only-few-confirmed/articleshow/55432386.cms

New Delhi. 28 Nov 2016. The civic authorities in Delhi have updated the official dengue toll in the city to 6, even as there was a slight rise in the number of cases of chikungunya over the last week. The South Delhi Municipal Corporation has updated the death tally for dengue from 4 to 6, according to a report released by the SDMC today [28 Nov 2016]. As per the report, 135 fresh dengue cases were reported in the national capital last week. 4200 cases were recorded till 26 Nov 2016.
http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/civic-bodies-update-official-dengue-toll-to-6-116112801181_1.html

New Delhi. 21 Nov 2016. Chikungunya cases continued to fall in the national capital, while dengue showed a slight rise in the past week, with the total number of people affected by the vector-borne disease crossing 4000 this season. Last year [2015], out of the 15 867 dengue cases, 7283 were reported in October 2015, the highest in the season. Also, September last year had seen 6775 cases but only 1362 cases were reported this September [2016]. At least 21 deaths due to dengue have been reported at various hospitals, including 9 at AIIMS, though the civic bodies said only 4 persons died of the disease this season. http://www.siasat.com/news/chikungunya-cases-fall-delhi-dengue-crosses-4k-mark-1070357/

- New Delhi. November 2016. In 2015, the media reported, quoting surveillance data, that dengue fever, caused by a virus transmitted by mosquito bite, killed 60 people in Delhi. However, government of Delhi data on medically certified deaths, largely unknown to the media, reveal the dengue death toll to be 486, or 8 times the media estimate. It is now apparent that both figures are underestimates because even the mortality data source listed under what is called Report on Medical Certification of Cause of Death is confined to 62.7 percent of registered deaths in hospital settings during 2015 in Delhi, a city of 17 million that reliably registers all deaths. This means the dengue death toll was higher than 486 because domiciliary deaths, or deaths taking place at homes, which comprise the 37.3 percent outside hospitals, were not accounted for.
http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/disappearing-dead-govt-media-got-no-of-dengue-deaths-in-delhi-wrong-116111700606_1.html

- Nagaland (Dimapur). 18 Nov 2016. With 33 new cases of dengue reported in Dimapur district in the last few weeks, the total number of people afflicted by the vector-borne disease has increased to 106.
http://www.easternmirrornagaland.com/33-new-dengue-cases-total-106/

- Nagaland (Dimapur). 14 Nov 2016. In an alarming rise in dengue cases, the Sentinel Surveillance Site Lab, District Hospital, Dimapur has confirmed 73 positive dengue cases out of 439 blood samples tested from October till 7 Nov 2016. According to reports, 21 samples were confirmed positive last Monday while 52 cases were tested positive some days earlier. The samples included collection from different private hospitals in and around Dimapur. This significant rise in the number of positive cases of dengue, which was only 8 as of 17 Oct 2016, is an indication that these are not sporadic cases. Recently, the Urban Vector-Borne Disease Control Scheme (UVBDCS) Dimapur suggested anti-dengue control measures by requesting the public and colony councils to observe a dry day social work once a week by draining all the water containers in order to control the mosquito population, which, it stated, would bring down the cases of dengue.
http://www.assamtribune.com/scripts/detailsnew.asp?id=nov1516/oth051

- Haryana/Punjab(Chandigarh & Mohali). 17 Nov 2016. As many as 25 fresh dengue cases were reported from Chandigarh and Mohali district today [17 Nov 2016]. Mohali district today reported 20 fresh cases of dengue and 8 of chikungunya. The total number of dengue cases in the district is now 2077 and that of chikungunya is 162. Chandigarh reported 5 fresh cases of dengue, taking the total number to 849. Four chikungunya cases were also reported from the city, taking the city's total to 246.
http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/chandigarh/community/25-fresh-dengue-cases-reported/324789.html

- Haryana/Punjab (Chandigarh & Mohali). 15 Nov 2016. Nine cases of dengue and 11 of chikungunya were reported from the tricity and surrounding areas today [15 Nov 2016]. Five cases of dengue were reported from Chandigarh, bringing the total count of dengue cases to 841 in the city. Three cases of chikungunya were also reported, taking the total number to 237. From Mohali district, 4 cases of dengue were reported, taking the number to 2057. Apart from that, 8 cases of chikungunya were also reported, taking the total count in the district to 154.
http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/chandigarh/community/more-cases-of-dengue-reported-from-tricity/323931.html

- Haryana/Punjab(Chandigarh & Mohali). 10 Nov 2016. The number of dengue cases in the tricity and the surrounding areas today reached 3032, while the total number in Mohali district alone crossed the 2022 mark. As many as 25 fresh cases were reported from Mohali district today. While no fresh case of chikungunya was reported from Mohali today, the total number of cases stands at 137. Meanwhile, 8 new cases of dengue were reported from Chandigarh today, taking the total number in the city to 822. The total count of chikungunya reached 227 with 4 new cases being reported today. Panchkula today reported one case of dengue.
http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/chandigarh/community/25-dengue-cases-reported-from-mohali/321675.html

- Haryana /Punjab(Chandigarh & Mohali). 7 Nov 2016. A total of 23 fresh cases of dengue and 10 of chikungunya were reported today [7 Nov 2016] from the tricity and surrounding areas. This includes 7 fresh cases of dengue and 5 of chikungunya from Chandigarh, while Mohali reported 12 fresh cases of dengue and 3 of chikungunya. Panchkula, meanwhile, reported 4 dengue and 2 chikungunya cases today.
http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/chandigarh/community/23-fresh-dengue-cases-reported-from-tricity/320389.html

- Punjab(Ludhiana). 25 Nov. 2016. Over 1300 dengue cases at Dayanand Medical College and Hospital (DMCH) alone
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ludhiana/Over-1300-dengue-cases-at-DMCH-alone/articleshow/55612862.cms

- Maharashtra (State). 28 Nov 2016. The number of deaths and infections caused by dengue in Maharashtra have risen significantly this year [2016]. It claimed the lives of 26 people between 1 Jan and 21 Nov this year [2016], while 6376 infections were reported. In comparison, there were 23 deaths and 4936 cases last year. According to the latest report released by the state health department, Kalyan-Dombivali Municipal Corporation recorded 5 deaths, the highest in Maharashtra. Rural parts of Thane and Nashik registered 3 casualties each during the same period. Of the 26 deaths, 14 deaths occurred within city limits of municipal corporations, while 12 others were in the state's rural parts.
A total of 4364 cases were recorded within the city limits of the state's different municipal corporations. The Brihanmumbai Municipal Corporation recorded the highest cases (1088) and had 2 deaths. The Nashik Municipal Corporation recorded 815 cases and 3 deaths, while the Pune Municipal Corporation had 611 cases and one death.
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/pune/Dengue-claims-26-lives-in-state/articleshow /55655695.cms

- Maharashtra (Mumbai). 28 Nov 2016. The number of dengue cases recorded in the city this year [2016] has been the highest in the last 6 years. However, the good news is that fatalities have declined significantly over the last 3 years. According to figures recently released by the state, Mumbai has recorded 1088 cases so far this year and 4 confirmed deaths. The last time dengue cases had crossed the 1000 mark was in 2012. Within the state too, the highest number of cases were reported from the city. Dengue infected 6376 people and claimed 26 lives in Maharashtra between 1 Jan and 21 Nov this year [2016].
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mumbai/Dengue-cases-in-Mumbai-highest-in-6-years/articleshow/55657471.cms

- Mizoram. 8 Nov 2016. 78 dengue cases in Mizoram since February [2016]
http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/78-dengue-cases-in-mizoram-since-february/1/805521.html

Pakistan
- Islamabad Capital Territory(ICT)/Punjab(Islamabad/Rawalpindi). 29 Nov 2016. 33 cases, one death reported in last one week. The 3 teaching hospitals in town, however, are still receiving sporadic cases of dengue fever as in the last one week, as many as 33 patients have been confirmed positive for the infection, while in the last 24 hours, only 2 patients were confirmed positive. The outbreak in the twin cities of Islamabad and Rawalpindi lost its intensity mainly because of a fall in temperatures, and according to health experts, the dengue fever patients being reported recently at the allied hospitals are those who contracted infection 3 to 7 days back.
https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/168476-Dengue-fever-outbreak-in-twin-cities-fades-away

- ICT/Punjab(Islamabad/Rawalpindi). 22 Nov 2016. Dengue fever outbreak in twin cities loses intensity. To date, the 3 teaching hospitals have tested as many as 3250 patients positive for the infection, of which nearly 60 per cent, well over 2000, are residents of the federal capital.
https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/166783-Dengue-fever-outbreak-in-twin-cities-loses-intensity
- ICT/Punjab(Islamabad/Rawalpindi). 20 Nov 2016. This year [2016], there has been a surge in the total number of dengue fever cases in the twin cities, though the bulk of cases reported have originated from Islamabad. Of the 3200 cases reported this year [2016], some 2200 have been reported from the capital. Over 700 have been reported from Rawalpindi.
http://tribune.com.pk/story/1236.866/rising-toll-woman-dies-dengue-pindi/
